## Factors which influence the growth cycles of flowering, such as flowering, fruiting, and ideal planting time
- All plants have an ideal range of [[Unsorted/Climate\|Climate]] conditions which they require to survive


### Plants that are living in conditions outside of their ideal range will undergo [[Stress\|Stress]], causing damage

### Primary factors that influence plant growth
- Light
	- Availability
	- Daylight hours
	- Spectral composition
	- Quality
		- Red and blue light have the biggest effect
			- Why grow lights appear violet
		- Green light is least effective, and mostly gets reflected
			- Generally is a waste of energy
			- Though the heat produced by this waste can be useful, it's more energy-efficient to use a dedicated heating system, such as thermal subsoil tubing
	- Effects of surplus
		- Plants can be sunburned
		- Increases temperature
	- Effects of defecit
		- Plants can starve
		- Decreases temperature
- Temperature
	- All plants have an ideal temperature range
	- Roots won't grow if the soil is the wrong temperaturethe sun
	- Effects of surplus
		- Plants undergo heat stress
		- Causes water to evaporate
	- Effects of defecit
		- Plants can freeze to death
		- Can cause water to freeze
			- Which causes significant damage to the water-based cells inside of plants
			- To prevent this, plants reduce the water content of their cells, and this concentrates their sugars and organic molecules into a sticky sap, which acts as antifreeze
- Water
	- The [[Unsorted/Water\|Water]] capacity of soils is critical to the health of plants
	- ![Pasted image 20221107115602.png|200](data:image/png;base64,) 
	- ![Pasted image 20221107120547.png](data:image/png;base64,)
	- ![Pasted image 20221107120536.png](data:image/png;base64,)
	- Types
		- Gravitational water
			- Water above the capacity of capilary water
			- ![Pasted image 20221107120202.png|200](data:image/png;base64,)
			- [[Unsorted/Soil#^978c8b\|Percolates]] out of [[Unsorted/Soil\|Soil]] after 24-48 hours
		- Capilary water
			- IE water getting sucked up into sand
			- Natural saturation point
		- Hygroscopic water
			- Water which is very tightly bound to soil particles
				- Not available to plantsplants
		- Chemically-bound water
			- IE the water that composes [[Unsorted/Clay\|Clay]]
